= Respective Contributions

The applicant, Nicholas Smotherman, will lead all aspects of the proposed research under the direction and mentorship of the sponsoring PI, Dr. Aleksandra Petelski. Specifically, the applicant will be responsible for the design and implementation of the KING graph neural network in Aim 1, including data acquisition from public repositories, training and validation of the model, and quantitative comparison of predictions against empirical measurements. The applicant will additionally perform all error-prone PCR, transfection, cell culture, and western blot experiments in Aim 2, as well as the statistical analysis comparing mutation thresholds across kinases. The applicant will be responsible for preparing publications, presenting findings at scientific meetings, and maintaining the public GitHub repository through which all code, data, and results will be released under a GPL-3.0 license.

The sponsoring PI will provide overall scientific direction, mentorship in experimental design and computational methods, and weekly one-on-one meetings to review progress and troubleshoot challenges. The sponsor will also assist in the development of the applicant's training plan, manuscript preparation, and grant-writing skills. Laboratory infrastructure, regulatory oversight, and access to shared institutional resources will be provided by the sponsor's lab.

A collaborator at the University of Florida will provide structural biology expertise and assist with experimental data acquisition relevant to Aim 1, including empirical NMR and HDX-MS measurements used to validate KING predictions. The collaborator will additionally serve as a backup resource for transfection work in Aim 2 should validation difficulties arise at the home institution.
